This species is a small tree, 3—5 m high, often bran ched, with broad leaves of about the same size as the leave of the papaya. The petals are particularly characteristi- with their reddish yellow colour and their upward·ben ends that form a sort of small pocket. The yellow fruit i broadest near its base3 its five angles are not very promi nent. The pulp is yellowish—white, rather acid and ver: juicy and fragrant. The taste and smel] of the fruit ar much the same in this species as in the following one an· in G. candamarcensis. The ovaries contain plenty of ovule but only few of these reach maturity. The ripe fruit- gene rally contains but 3-4 seeds and often not a single one.
